description.text: A couple of 3D printable logos for my old model rocket company.

Finally got a Chris Reeves small insingo and decided to try and model it, its not perfect by any means but size and shape are pretty representative. I've only printed handles so far, blade is thin and causes some issues. If I can get it to work I will upload the rest of hardware (spacers, stops etc.) UPDATE: removed old blade added a thicker edged one an printed it standing up, this worked very well. assembled knife with one sided spacers and glued in place (hollow spacers and actual hardware could also be used) https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=P10fmmA0HEU&feature=youtu.b

I went a little nutzo designing more of these than I need for another project in progress until I got some that I liked. I wanted something that mimicked Bauhaus geometric purity and also had a big flat side to make them easy for 3D printing. These bar-nuts are designed around a 1/4" SAE nut with a 7/16 hexagonal head, but could probably be scaled to other sizes. Print them out and drop the nut down the hexagonal hole and clamp down.

Printed in 2 pieces, this box and lid are designed to display up to four of the customized photographic lithopanes.Please note that you can put your very own photographic images in the place holders! You must purchase a clip light to insert into the base of the box in order to light it from the inside.   The seam lines in the photograph are on my prototype only and will not be present when the box is printed as a single unit. Please see the instructions for details on the lithopanes that will fit this box.

I found that the box is best printed in one piece (the photos show seam lines that would NOT be present when it is printed as a single piece) and the lid printed separately. The customized lithopanes: http://www.thingiverse.com/apps/customizer/run?thing_id=74322: allow you to choose and print your own photographic images. The box has 4 place holders that up to 4 of these lithopanes can be glued into for display. The size and details of the lithopane that fits this box are as follows: Picture Shape = HD Wide (not standard), Picture Orientation = horizontal, Pane Size = small, Invert Colors = yes check the box, Include Hole (under ADJUSTMENTS tab) = no, Layer Height = 0.2, Number of layers = 20 An example of the clip light that fits into the base can be seen here: http://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B000VX6A5K/ref=oh_details_o00_s00_i00?ie=UTF8&psc=1 I strongly recomment switching out the bulb for an led one that does not get hot! This is a nice bright one: http://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B00CRHG63Y/ref=oh_details_o02_s00_i00?ie=UTF8&psc=1 If you choose to put lithopanes in all of the available panels you would be printing 6 separate components: 4 Lithopane images + 1 box + 1 lid.

title: Another Budget Bookmark - Clip w/ Reading Aid

description.text:
Another of my budget bookmarks.  This one is extremely thin (approx .020" thick, about 6 post-it sheets together), flexible and quick to make.  It is around 4 inches long and 2 inches wide.  Similar to the Nana and Grandma bookmarks, but harder to lose!  It is based off of countless ones i have seen in the stores.  
This one has a reading window in the center of the bookmark for those that sometimes need single line reading assistance.  My son has a hard time with focusing on one line at a time while reading verses, so this helps reduce the distraction of the surrounding lines.  The window is around 2.22" wide and .2" tall.  Works for the bibles we have, but you may have to trim the window wider if you have larger type.  But that is easy, since it is so thin.  Hope you find it useful.  Happy Printing!
Print it and use! It is very thin, so it will be done in a jiffy!

description.text: While on a trip to Japan I saw something like this, when I got back I made one out of clay, now it's 3d time.
Print, pour sauce inside the mouth, enjoy.

My nut got stuck while wearing in the threads. Luckily I had a 3D printer so that I could print the remedy! I am sure that this have and will happen to more of us, so here you go, fitted wrenches! The inside dimension is 47,5 mm to give a snug fit around bbuonomos bolt and nut found at http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:4880 I have included the Solidworks part files as well if you want them. UPDATE 1:
After printing and testing the first wrench I redesigned it and now it prints in less than half the time, and looks cooler :D

First count the sides on your bolt, I didn't and ended up printing the wrong wrench at first :) Download the appropriate file and print. I used 1.2 mm walls and top/bottom because I like strong tools. With thick walls like that, I see no point in going above 20% infill. File selection guide:
47_5_8sided_slim_H_10mm - Probably what you want, quick and nice looking. 10 mm high. 47_5mm_8sided.STL - A larger and earlier version of the wrench, 20 mm high, takes a long time to print. 47_5mm_6sided.STL - A hex-wrench for traditionalist, as of now it WON'T WORK with the "Large Threaded Bolt and Nut by bbuonomo"-thing since it was 8-sided last time I saw it :)

My daughter needed a blunt theater prop sword for a school play called "Peggy the pint sized pirate"..  Overall length, about 60cm's or about two feet.. The longest piece is just under 250mm (Obviously recommend PLA)  Printed on a Mendlemax with Maker's Tool Works build platform.  Have fun!  
Bottom of the hilt is open, my daughter wanted to put some sort of hilt ornament in it..

Parts are snug, I do recommend that you plastic weld to secure the bottom half of the sword to the hilt.  And again on the puzzle connection between the upper and lower pieces of blade.  I print at .1 infill so its really light and can break fairly easily in actual use...  But that does make heating for welding the parts together slightly problematic...

description.text:
Print this and attach it to the bottom of a ceramic mug. If your mug is slightly smaller, wrap it with some electrical tape.

Have fun with it! Please feel free to add to it and improve. Check out the youtube video at:
